Increasing my forecast again. I was at 60% for a long time, then went to 25% 10 days ago, thinking my forecast had been too high. But with inflation coming in higher than models expected, additional Fed rate hikes (today + planned), the expected housing market downturn, a Covid surge coming in the fall and winter, and who knows, potentially additional energy market disturbances because of Russia and/or China, I think the risk of both quarters seeing negative growth is not small. Oh, and then there's FedEx. I feel like a lot of models have been too rosy, but maybe I'm wrong.

Historically, If any quarter 'q' is negative, the chances of the 'q + 2' & 'q + 3' quarters also being negative is 11% (4 times out of 44)

I see low chance for US real GDP growth to be negative in both 3Q22 and 4Q22 for now, as the Fed will probably adjust its monetary policy to accommodate. Also, 2Q22 GDP growth will probably be weak given the lockdown in China. With these, it is likely to see positive sequential GDP growth in at least one of 3Q22 and 4Q22. However, if there are any additional negative external shock, we may negative sequential US GDP growth in both 3Q22 and 4Q22.

First estimate of Q1GDP is negative. The recession is starting much earlier than estimated. This is not transitory. This is not caused by the Ukraine war. This is a massive bubble popping and it will take a while to correct itself.

Two periods of real GDP contraction constitute a recession. The US had 21 such recessions in the 20th century, and has experienced 2 such in the 21st century, or 11 in total, since the end of WW2. They tend to last at least 8 months, but few longer than one year. As I'm expecting the US Q1 2022 GDP to show contraction, that would mark the beginning of a new recession. Now 3 of the 11 post WW2 recessions were longer than 1 year so I'm using 3/11 or 27% as my base chance of this recession lasting until at least the end of Q4 2022. Wars such as WW2 and Korea have reliably lead to recessions and we have Ukraine going on. The two previous oil crises have each lead to recessions of longer than one year (100%), and we are indeed in the middle of an oil crisis. Finally, both the financial crises of 1929 and 2007 lead to recessions longer than one year (100%) and we are experiencing such a crisis due to over-supply of money and high debt levels. Given the combination of oil and financial crises with an ongoing war, I believe the chance will be raised considerably. I'm going to allow for the possibility of a rapid return to normal should the oil and financial impacts be resolved quickly, just in time for Q4, but I don't consider that likely.

The economy is hot (employment markets and capacity) still so it will take awhile for the effects of inflation to slow the economy down enough to stall speed.
Interest rate hikes increase chance of recession. But, residual pent up demand could float things in one or both quarters in question.

It is likely that the Fed will set a further 50 basis point increase on interest rates to offset inflation. The announcement is expected fairly soon. This is likely to induce an effect on growth in order to dampen inflation. This increases the likelihood of stagflation for 2022, implying possible contraction in estimates for Q3 and Q4. However, contraction can occur without negative growth.

The fact the the question addresses "real GDP" is important. Inflationary pressure will likely lead to reduced purchasing power, unless wages keep pace. While it is far less likely that we will see nominal GDP decrease in both quarters, there is a very real chance that real GDP will fall. The question is whether 3Q will fall, followed by a contingent question if 4Q will also fall. These types of conditional questions should have a lower base rate until the first condition is met.

Stagflation for the US has a high likelihood of occurring as we move into Q3 and Q4. While various instruments used in monetary policy will move at a faster rate (2022), projections indicate a contraction relative to Q2 outcomes. Covid-19, the war in Ukraine, a rise in commodity prices and current inflation all factor into these growth estimates.
